Selected models:¶
  • Best Overall (RF + SMOTE)
  • Best With PCA (RF + SMOTE + PCA(5)
  • Best XGBoost (PCA(9))
  • Best Logistic

Overall Random Forest without reducing the dataset with PCA seems to offer the best results (using PCA seems to slightly offer similar result just with poorer results when predicting wines of with highest quality rating(8))

XGBoost is more accurate at predicting the middle classes with poorer results for the bottom/top classes.

Overall none of the model provide good result. Even when using various balancing techniques like SMOTE (in this case the best results were achieved by manually specifying sampling strategy for the underrepresented classes) they still strong struggle to detect the classes which are underrepresented in the initial dataset. This indicates that either/both:

  • there is not enough data in the dataset for the lowest/highest quality wines to build a robust model
  • quality scores are assigned arbitrarily/using other data not included in the dataset and the chemical properties dataset can't be used to distinguish wines which have similar quality rating.

However, all the models seem to still detect the ordinal nature of the dataset. .e.g none of the wines in the highest quality category are classified as being in the bottom one and very few in the second-lowest one.

Based on this we can try and simplify our objective by just trying to predict high vs low quality wines instead of the exact quality score.

Binary Classification¶

To achieve our initial objective (designing a model which could be used by wine merchants to select high quality wines) we don't really need to determine its exact quality rating, just determine whether the wine is "good" would be enough.

To accomplish that we'll binarize the quality rating defined as wines which have a quality higher than 6 as good:

quality_over_7_or_more
0    1382
1     217
Name: count, dtype: int64

We can see that the dataset is heavily imbalanced, so we'll apply the balancing techniques (SMOTE or Class Weighting) we have used previously:

We can see that the results are considerably better with both RF and XGBoost offering decent precision and recall scores:

<Figure size 800x600 with 0 Axes>
<Figure size 800x600 with 0 Axes>

Unfortunately both RF and XGBoost still struggle to correctly classify high quality wines with about ~30% of them classified as low quality. However, relatively few low quality wines are misclassified as high the models might still be suitable for our goals. While this is not really fair to those winemakers whose high quality wines are excluded a bigger concern from the meechant/distributors perspective would be accidentally buying too many poor wines.
